response.name: Marina Electrical Repair
response.summary:
Project Description: Marina Electrical Upgrades

This project entails a comprehensive overhaul of the marina's electrical systems, designed to enhance functionality, safety, and durability. The scope of work includes:

Main Dock Panel Installation:

Provide and install a new 200-amp dock panel with all-new GFCI breakers.

Include a corrosion-resistant housing for the dock panel to ensure longevity and protection in the marine environment.

Rewiring of 16 Slips:

Rewire 16 slips using two-pole 30A breakers for each slip.

Supply and install new Tech 2 controllers for each of the 16 boat lifts.

Provide new 30A wiring to power the lifts, including upsizing feed wires to #8 THHN (240V) to accommodate increased electrical demands.

Install new motor wiring for each lift and connect it to the Tech 2 controllers, housed within Schedule 80 PVC pipe for durability and environmental protection.

Ensure all piping complies with NEC pipe fill requirements.

Wet Slip Feeder Upgrade:

Provide and install new 120V feeders for 16 wet slips.

Upsize feeder wires to #10 THHN for improved performance and reliability.

Use Schedule 80 PVC pipe for all wiring, ensuring compliance with NEC pipe fill standards.

GFCI Outlet Installation:

Install new 20A GFCI outlets for all 32 lifts, ensuring compliance with safety standards.

Provide FS boxes and water-resistant covers for all outlets to enhance safety in wet environments.

Lift Motor Wiring:

Install new motor wiring for each of the 16 boat lifts, housed within Schedule 80 PVC pipe to enhance durability and protection.

Lighting and Water Pedestals:

Provide and install new light pedestals, each equipped with integrated water spigots for user convenience.

Supply new 120V wiring to each pedestal, housed in Schedule 80 PVC pipe, and divide the pedestals into two sections, with each section operated by a photocell for automated functionality.

Hardware and Attachments:

Use stainless steel hardware for all attachments to ensure corrosion resistance and durability in the marine environment.

Breaker Compliance:

Ensure all newly installed breakers, including those for the pedestals and slips, are GFCI breakers to uphold the highest safety standards

This upgrade project will be carried out with strict adherence to the National Electrical Code (NEC) and best practices for marina electrical systems. The work will improve the marina's operational efficiency and ensure a safe environment for users.

response.name: 12 Dock disconnect / reconnect
response.summary:
Phase 1: Disconnect and Secure Existing Dock Feeds
Disconnect the existing electrical feeds from all 12 docks.

Pull the wire back to the junction box (Jbox).

Cap the ends of the wires to ensure safety and prevent any electrical hazards.

Phase 2: Install New Feeder Pipe Through Corrugated Seawall
Place the new feeder pipe through the newly constructed corrugated seawall.

Secure the pipe in position and ensure it is properly aligned.

Reconnect the pipe before the backfilling of dirt is completed, ensuring it is ready for the final wiring.

Phase 3: Pull and Test New Wire
Pull the new wire through the feeder pipe to all 12 docks.

Test for power and verify that each connection is functioning correctly.

Ensure all systems are operational and meet the required safety standards.

This project will be executed in close coordination with the seawall builders and landscapers, following behind their construction schedule to minimize disruptions and ensure a smooth workflow.
